title: For Sale/Trade:  Interarms 30-06 Mark X Mauser and 90 rounds
location: North Side by 1960 and I-45, Houston, Texas
postcontent:
A Mauser Mark-X is a Commercial Mauser made by Zastava Arms out of eastern Europe and imported and sold by Interarms. They are good rifles that hold up very well.  After Interarms stopped importing them, Charles Daly imported them as the Daly Mauser for several years, until Zastava gave their contract to Remington.  Remington installs the barreled actions on nicer wood stocks and markets it as a 798. Same barreled action as before, but prettier and much more expensive.  

The Whitworth company in Manchester England,bought actions, rebarreled them and gave the actions more final finishing. They are thus a bit smoother and desirable. From Manchester, they sold some barreled actions to Interarms which did the restocking here with Italian made stocks and marketed the finished rifles in the US.

Just like the description says.  It comes with a generic 4.5-12x30 scope, sling and bore snake for cleaning it, and 90 rounds of Remington 165 grain Core-Lokt ammunition.  A pretty sweet rifle that has killed a couple deer and some pigs.  I'm selling it to raise money for a new handgun or whatever.

title: For Sale:  Charter Arms AR-7 Explorer breakdown survival rifle
postcontent:
This is a Charter Arms AR-7 "Explorer", made in Stratford, Connecticut in the 1970-80s.  Invented by Eugene Stoner (father of the M-16 and AR-15), it was intended to be a survival gun for military pilots, that they could bail out with.  The barrel, receiver and magazine all come off and stow inside of the hollow stock, and the buttplate makes the whole thing watertight.  It's semi-auto with a 10-round mag.  Due to the use of aluminum, it weighs less than 3 pounds!  The US military never officially adopted the gun but the Israeli military used them.  

The gun was first produced by Armalite from 1959-73, during which it appeared in the James Bond films "From Russia with Love" and "Goldfinger".  Armalite sold the rights, dies, etc., to Charter Arms who produced the gun from 1973-89 or '90.  Since then, the gun has been produced by other makers.  This one is one of Charter Arms' versions.  They have become very popular as bug-out / SHtF gun.  It's easily backpackable and, since it shoots .22LR, plinking or varmint hunting is cheap, easy and fun.  


I bought the gun at an estate sale.  Since it was disassembled and the pieces were stowed in the stock, the liquidator assumed it was part of a toy gun!  The gun is in good shape.  There are very superficial scrapes and mars to the plastic stock, but the butt-cap fits tightly so I have every reason to believe it would indeed float.  The barrel looks to be totally straight, the bore is shiny and the feed ramp looks to be undamaged.  I ran 50 rounds through it and I never had a mis-fire or jam.  There is some minor edgewear to the black-painted aluminum parts as well as some very minor scratches, but it's still quite presentable.  It hasn't been modified, damaged or repaired in any way that I can see.  

I'm in San Francisco.  I'll be happy to deliver it within SF for free, or within the BART corridor for the cost of the ticket.  I can ship it within CA for $20.  PayPal if I have to ship it, cash in person.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Official US Army Remington M24 Sniper Rifle Pending Payment
postcontent:
As the title says. This is an original\official Remington M24 US Army Sniper Rifle. 

A couple of notes up front:

1. This is for the rifle only. It no longer has a scope, bi-pod or sling. The original scope base is included

2. The rifle is, IMO, in need of a new Barrel see details below but will only shoot 1.5 MOA with 168gr match and has excessive freebore of over 1.5 "

3. Bolt is official but newer. I was told the Armor put a new issue bolt in it. Three gunsmith's have confirmed the bolt is fairly new with low rounds. It bears the official "M" stamp with Circle on it as it should.

4. The previous owner started to do some customizing on this. Barrel and Bolt where fluted and I was told the receiver is bedded. Work was performed by High Tech Customs. I brought the rifle to them and they confirmed they did the fluting but could not remember about bedding without pulling old records

As you know only a few of these hit the civilian market. You can google the details but most where commissioned back to Remington to be re-utilized for the new M2010 rifle. A few where made available to qualified Military which is where this one comes in. I bought this off a retired Army Soldier with the intent of building a good LR rifle back in 2010 or so. It sat in the safe for a couple of years and recently I started to look at the project again. Range trip with Hornady A-max 168 gr 5 shot groups where at best 1.5 MOA. This puzzled me a bit and I purchased a COL gauge and measures the free bore. It is over 1.5 inches. Thinking the chamber is shot I brought back to High Tech and they confirmed my fears. They recommended re-barreling the rifle  with an Lylja three groove heavy profile.

After much sole searching I have decided not to pursue this project further so I will leave it up to someone else. Putting a new Lylja barrel on it would definitely make it a real player in the game. Since the M24 was built on the long action you can easily step it up to the 300 Win. mag with the new barrel and upgrading the extractor or re-barrel in 308 or leave as is.

Anyway - time to let her go to the next person. I can send more pictures. Please reply with M24 in the subject line and with an email or phone number. If these are not present I will ignore. I don't need to sell so please  no low ball offers.

I will require transfer at FFL buyer to cover transfer fees and background check.

I am listing with my base price with a Best offer. This could be higher than my list price if there is a large response.

I prefer local face to face but if outside state interested party is willing to cover all costs for transfer\packing\shipping etc I may consider.
